.TH TB-HELP 1 "December 2025" "ToolBox 1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
tb-help \- show help for a command
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B tb help
[\fB\-\-context\fR \fICONTEXT\fR]
.I COMMAND
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B tb help
command displays detailed help information for a specific command, including its description and the actual shell command it executes. The help shown is context-specific, meaning it shows information for the command in the current project context (or a specified context).
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-\-context " " \fICONTEXT\fR
Show help for the command in a specific context instead of the detected context
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B tb help build
Show help for the 'build' command in the current context
.PP
.in +4n
.nf
In a Node.js project (package.json detected):

Command: build
Context: node
Description: Build the project
Shell Command: npm run build
.fi
.in
.TP
.B tb help \-\-context go build
Show help for the 'build' command in the Go context
.PP
.in +4n
.nf
Command: build
Context: go
Description: Build all packages
Shell Command: go build ./...
.fi
.in
.TP
.B tb help \-\-context ubuntu-packaging gbranch
Show help for the 'gbranch' command in the Ubuntu packaging context
.PP
.in +4n
.nf
Command: gbranch
Context: ubuntu-packaging
Description: Create/checkout git branch: gbranch <project> <bug-id> [merge|sru|bug] [description]
Shell Command: bash ~/.cache/toolbox/ubuntu_helpers.sh gbranch
.fi
.in
.SH CONTEXT DETECTION
When run without \fB\-\-context\fR, help uses the same context detection as regular commands:
.TP
1.
Scans current directory for marker files (package.json, go.mod, etc.)
.TP
2.
Selects the first matching context
.TP
3.
Shows help for the command in that context
.PP
Use \fB\-\-verbose\fR to see which context was detected:
.PP
.in +4n
.nf
tb help build -v
.fi
.in
.SH AVAILABLE COMMANDS
The available commands depend on the current context. Common commands across contexts include:
.TP
.B build
Build the project
.TP
.B test
Run tests
.TP
.B start
Start the application
.TP
.B dev
Start development server
.TP
.B lint
Run linter
.TP
.B fmt
Format code
.TP
.B install
Install dependencies
.TP
.B run
Run the application
.PP
Use
.B tb plugin list
and
.B tb plugin info <plugin>
to see plugin-specific commands.
